I already got the answer,  u humans are decades behind my technology

I will lend some hints:  it&#39;s not A photon, in fact photons are nonexistence particles (with that current meaning).  What it&#39;s more close to is a wave &#39;beep&#39;

oh, and of course, probability is directly related to proportions; 

what is a probability for an individual stuff, is the proportion for a large number of stuff; so if the probability of the photon arriving at some space is say 30%, in time, 30% of photons will arrive there; 

but this only becomes visible when you have large number of stuff (photons); otherwise the effect is much more subtle and seems random

indeed, what is really interesting is how this related to the Heisenberg uncertainty principle

the direction in which a photon travels relates to its momentum and momentum and position are directly correlated via the uncertainty principle; the variation in one leads to the opposite variation in the other; 

so when you squish the photon in such a small space, you increasing the certainty of its position; you&#39;re increasing the uncertainty of the momentum;

are almost always of the shape of waves in QM; 

so basically photons are particles but if you plotted the probability of the photon of existing at some point in space against the space itself the graph would look like a wave; 

this is where wave-particle duality comes from; it&#39;s not that weird when you look into the math of it
